(I will let the ingredients shine.)

500
00:15:53,502 --> 00:15:56,701
(Sam Kim, the chef dedicated to natural cooking)

501
00:15:56,702 --> 00:15:59,301
(I will show you a taste of pure indulgence.)

502
00:15:59,302 --> 00:16:02,642
(Jung Ho Young, the master of Japanese cuisine)

503
00:16:02,812 --> 00:16:04,542
(I'm here to win.)

504
00:16:04,742 --> 00:16:06,782
(A culinary showdown with no room to back down)

505
00:16:06,952 --> 00:16:09,392
(The drawback of Sam's food is his focus on natural cooking.)

506
00:16:11,652 --> 00:16:13,522
(The fish broke!)

507
00:16:13,952 --> 00:16:16,051
(You broke the fish when we managed to keep it intact.)

508
00:16:16,052 --> 00:16:17,991
(I can totally predict what Ho Young is going to cook.)

509
00:16:17,992 --> 00:16:20,432
(He will deep-fry something, make it sweet, or braise it.)

510
00:16:21,232 --> 00:16:22,592
(Pouring)

511
00:16:22,832 --> 00:16:23,932
(My fritters are ruined.)

512
00:16:24,202 --> 00:16:26,031
- It's ruined.
- They're stuck!

513
00:16:26,032 --> 00:16:27,502
(Guys, his fritters are ruined!)

514
00:16:27,702 --> 00:16:32,202
(The culinary showdown is coming soon.)

515
00:16:32,572 --> 00:16:34,171
- You're really going to drive?
- Yes.

516
00:16:34,172 --> 00:16:35,271
(They will spend the whole day with their team.)

517
00:16:35,272 --> 00:16:36,312
No way.

518
00:16:37,442 --> 00:16:38,511
- Are we heading out right away?
- Then...

519
00:16:38,512 --> 00:16:39,728
(His eyes are filled with excitement.)

520
00:16:39,752 --> 00:16:41,011
You're really going to drive?

521
00:16:41,012 --> 00:16:43,521
We do drive ourselves depending on the theme.

522
00:16:43,522 --> 00:16:44,882
(Sam is fascinated by everything.)

523
00:16:45,452 --> 00:16:48,121
(The best driver, Se Yoon, turns the steering wheel smoothly.)

524
00:16:48,122 --> 00:16:49,722
(Impressed)

525
00:16:49,992 --> 00:16:51,161
You have a lot of experience driving, right?

526
00:16:51,162 --> 00:16:52,521
(He's full of curiosity as it's been a while.)

527
00:16:52,522 --> 00:16:53,562
Yes.

528
00:16:54,232 --> 00:16:56,262
- My gosh.
- Wait, you have to drive?

529
00:16:56,362 --> 00:16:57,562
- Yes. That's right.
- I see.

530
00:16:57,932 --> 00:16:59,931
You can speak casually to me.

531
00:16:59,932 --> 00:17:01,771
- Please speak casually to us.
- Okay.

532
00:17:01,772 --> 00:17:02,832
Treat me however you want.

533
00:17:03,342 --> 00:17:04,372
Okay.

534
00:17:04,572 --> 00:17:07,741
I'll be honest. Since we're in Mokpo,

535
00:17:07,742 --> 00:17:09,812
Japanese cuisine might have an upper hand.

536
00:17:10,112 --> 00:17:11,141
- Right.
- Of course.

537
00:17:11,142 --> 00:17:12,982
- There's a lot of seafood.
- Of course it is.

538
00:17:13,082 --> 00:17:14,481
I have a good feeling about this.

539
00:17:14,482 --> 00:17:17,621
- I have a very good feeling.
- It was on "Chef and My Fridge."

540
00:17:17,622 --> 00:17:18,651
Yes.

541
00:17:18,652 --> 00:17:19,681
Sam was asked to cook a dish from a different cuisine.

542
00:17:19,682 --> 00:17:20,752
And he wasn't good at it.

543
00:17:21,992 --> 00:17:22,992
I'm serious.

544
00:17:22,993 --> 00:17:24,553
He went up against Chef Park Eun Yeong.

545
00:17:24,792 --> 00:17:27,432
They were supposed to swap their cuisines, Chinese and Italian.

546
00:17:27,762 --> 00:17:28,832
He struggled with that.

547
00:17:29,462 --> 00:17:30,862
You're badmouthing him right away.

548
00:17:31,432 --> 00:17:32,831
Right after we got in the car.

549
00:17:32,832 --> 00:17:33,971
His range is limited.

550
00:17:33,972 --> 00:17:34,972
(Stubborn)

551
00:17:34,973 --> 00:17:36,841
But I can cook other cuisines like Chinese, Korean,

552
00:17:36,842 --> 00:17:38,372
- and Japanese.
- Of course.

553
00:17:38,842 --> 00:17:40,218
- I can do it all.
- He's an all-rounder.

554
00:17:40,242 --> 00:17:41,671
I bet it will be an easy victory.

555
00:17:41,672 --> 00:17:43,312
By the way, were you close to Sam...

556
00:17:43,812 --> 00:17:46,011
even before "Culinary Class Wars?"

557
00:17:46,012 --> 00:17:47,312
- We were close.
- Okay.

558
00:17:47,712 --> 00:17:50,622
We often talked on the phone.

559
00:17:50,722 --> 00:17:52,151
- Even before the show?
- Yes, we had been close.

560
00:17:52,152 --> 00:17:53,722
- We called each other...
- Yes.

561
00:17:53,892 --> 00:17:55,751
- almost every day during COVID-19.
- Really?

562
00:17:55,752 --> 00:17:56,791
- "How are you doing?"
- Why?

563
00:17:56,792 --> 00:17:58,691
- We had no customers back then.
- Things were tough then?

564
00:17:58,692 --> 00:18:02,232
But even then we didn't speak casually to each other.

565
00:18:02,892 --> 00:18:04,732
- We called each other Chef.
- Really?

566
00:18:05,202 --> 00:18:08,402
After going up against each other on "Culinary Class Wars,"

567
00:18:08,932 --> 00:18:10,271
we bonded more.

568
00:18:10,272 --> 00:18:12,501
- Then...
- You guys bonded on that show.

569
00:18:12,502 --> 00:18:14,342
The show brought us even closer.

570
00:18:14,412 --> 00:18:16,532
He said yes when I asked him to do something with me.

571
00:18:16,712 --> 00:18:18,111
After starring on...

572
00:18:18,112 --> 00:18:20,252
- "Culinary Class Wars,"
- Yes.

573
00:18:20,312 --> 00:18:22,181
You built quite a following among young kids.

574
00:18:22,182 --> 00:18:23,981
- I have a lot of young fans.
- Right.

575
00:18:23,982 --> 00:18:25,821
- Like elementary school kids?
- Yes.

576
00:18:25,822 --> 00:18:27,022
Why do they like you so much?

577
00:18:27,392 --> 00:18:29,991
I get teased a lot on the show.

578
00:18:29,992 --> 00:18:31,438
(The chef who gets teased a lot receives a lot of sympathy.)

579
00:18:31,462 --> 00:18:32,861
- After you got eliminated, - Yes.

580
00:18:32,862 --> 00:18:34,891
Who teased you the most?

581
00:18:34,892 --> 00:18:37,301
It has to be my son.

582
00:18:37,302 --> 00:18:38,462
- Really?
- Your son?

583
00:18:38,562 --> 00:18:40,102
- You guys must be super close.
- Yes.

584
00:18:40,302 --> 00:18:42,301
"Dad, you got eliminated? Darn it."

585
00:18:42,302 --> 00:18:43,602
No. Let me give you an example.

586
00:18:44,202 --> 00:18:45,802
Let's say Chef Ho Young is on TV.

587
00:18:46,612 --> 00:18:48,011
"That's the chef who beat you."

588
00:18:48,012 --> 00:18:49,472
(Smirking)

589
00:18:49,842 --> 00:18:50,842
- No way.
- Gosh.

590
00:18:51,582 --> 00:18:52,711
You should've asked him,

591
00:18:52,712 --> 00:18:54,652
- "Did Ho Young send you?"
- So cute.

592
00:18:55,052 --> 00:18:56,311
"Did he tell you to say that?"

593
00:18:56,312 --> 00:18:58,852
Even my son teased me about losing.

594
00:18:59,252 --> 00:19:00,721
But you should feel some pressure today.

595
00:19:00,722 --> 00:19:03,462
On "Culinary Class Wars," only you got eliminated.

596
00:19:03,862 --> 00:19:05,621
If we lose, we won't be able to eat.

597
00:19:05,622 --> 00:19:07,032
- Really?
- Yes.

598
00:19:07,762 --> 00:19:09,492
- We have to win no matter what.
- Please.

599
00:19:09,632 --> 00:19:11,392
- Please do your best.
- Let's say you lose.

600
00:19:11,462 --> 00:19:13,571
- It doesn't solely depend on me.
- Then...

601
00:19:13,572 --> 00:19:14,972
- All of us must do our best.
- No.

602
00:19:15,332 --> 00:19:16,692
- It will be your fault.
- Really?

603
00:19:17,272 --> 00:19:19,912
If we lose, it might get awkward in the car later.

604
00:19:20,772 --> 00:19:23,171
If we lose, you might have to drive.

605
00:19:23,172 --> 00:19:25,112
- You can drive, right?
- Yes, I can.

606
00:19:25,882 --> 00:19:27,511
We'll be polite for now.

607
00:19:27,512 --> 00:19:28,852
(It's fun to tease him.)

608
00:19:29,482 --> 00:19:31,251
Honestly, this might be the last time.

609
00:19:31,252 --> 00:19:33,292
(They're happily heading to their destination.)

610
00:19:34,152 --> 00:19:36,222
- We're at a restaurant.
- Let's go inside.

611
00:19:37,092 --> 00:19:39,212
- We'll have a meal this early?
- It looks delicious.

612
00:19:39,892 --> 00:19:40,991
Oh, my.

613
00:19:40,992 --> 00:19:42,231
- You're giving us food already?
- Gosh.

614
00:19:42,232 --> 00:19:44,201
We're starting off at a restaurant.

615
00:19:44,202 --> 00:19:46,061
- Why...
- This place...

616
00:19:46,062 --> 00:19:47,201
We've never gotten a meal...

617
00:19:47,202 --> 00:19:48,431
- this early on our show.
- Right?

618
00:19:48,432 --> 00:19:49,471
- Really?
- Gosh.

619
00:19:49,472 --> 00:19:50,801
(Puzzled)

620
00:19:50,802 --> 00:19:53,412
I told you earlier that it would be a culinary trip.

621
00:19:54,112 --> 00:19:56,412
- Really?
- Sam said...

622
00:19:56,712 --> 00:19:58,081
when traveling in Mokpo,

623
00:19:58,082 --> 00:19:59,911
everyone had to try some octopus.

624
00:19:59,912 --> 00:20:01,481
- That's right.
- Right.

625
00:20:01,482 --> 00:20:03,422
- The thin-legged octopus.
- Nicely done.

626
00:20:03,822 --> 00:20:06,892
The thin-legged octopus is a famous local ingredient.

627
00:20:07,022 --> 00:20:08,351
Its bouncy texture...

628
00:20:08,352 --> 00:20:10,521
and rich sweetness of the octopus especially stand out.

629
00:20:10,522 --> 00:20:11,562
I love it.

630
00:20:11,692 --> 00:20:13,161
A complete octopus meal of Mokpo...

631
00:20:13,162 --> 00:20:15,732
(A complete octopus meal of Mokpo)

632
00:20:15,832 --> 00:20:17,061
and the benefit...

633
00:20:17,062 --> 00:20:18,838
to pick the main ingredient of the culinary showdown...

634
00:20:18,862 --> 00:20:20,031
will be at stake on this mission,

635
00:20:20,032 --> 00:20:22,102
- I love food.
- Food Mafia in Mokpo.

636
00:20:22,272 --> 00:20:23,842
- Mafia?
- Mafia?

637
00:20:24,072 --> 00:20:25,171
(Looking forward to it)

638
00:20:25,172 --> 00:20:27,348
- The meal is a good benefit, but...
- The ingredients?

639
00:20:27,372 --> 00:20:30,211
You will get another benefit to pick the main ingredients later.

640
00:20:30,212 --> 00:20:31,241
- It's important.
- The octopus...

641
00:20:31,242 --> 00:20:32,382
- Hold on.
- Yes.

642
00:20:32,882 --> 00:20:34,582
- He talked about this in the car.
- Okay.

643
00:20:35,412 --> 00:20:38,151
Is olive oil one of the ingredients?

644
00:20:38,152 --> 00:20:39,152
Will it be provided...

645
00:20:39,152 --> 00:20:40,152
- as a basic ingredient?
- It must be a basic ingredient.

646
00:20:40,153 --> 00:20:41,351
- It must be a basic ingredient.
- It must be a basic ingredient.

647
00:20:41,352 --> 00:20:44,622
He said that Sam couldn't cook anything without olive oil.

648
00:20:45,422 --> 00:20:47,091
- Wait.
- Like a kid without his mom,

649
00:20:47,092 --> 00:20:48,791
he would get restless and wouldn't know what to do.

650
00:20:48,792 --> 00:20:51,032
- "Give me olive oil." Really?
- That's what I heard.

651
00:20:51,232 --> 00:20:52,701
- Well...
- Is that true?

652
00:20:52,702 --> 00:20:54,171
You can't use cooking oil or soybean oil?

653
00:20:54,172 --> 00:20:56,801
- I can, but it'll improve my food.
- Right.

654
00:20:56,802 --> 00:21:00,311
You know what? He just teased you about your use of olive oil.

655
00:21:00,312 --> 00:21:02,012
- What can't he cook without then?
- He...

656
00:21:02,112 --> 00:21:03,942
He can't cook without sugar or cooking wine.

657
00:21:04,112 --> 00:21:05,941
"Give me sugar and cooking wine!"

658
00:21:05,942 --> 00:21:07,182
- "Cooking wine!"
- "Sugar!

659
00:21:07,312 --> 00:21:08,581
I can't cook without them.

660
00:21:08,582 --> 00:21:10,181
(Quietly agreeing)

661
00:21:10,182 --> 00:21:12,222
They just provoked each other.

662
00:21:12,552 --> 00:21:15,292
All right, everyone. It's spring now.

663
00:21:15,952 --> 00:21:18,122
We'll show you the main ingredients first.

664
00:21:18,362 --> 00:21:19,391
They look great.

665
00:21:19,392 --> 00:21:21,031
- Pen shells look great.
- Flounder is no joke in spring.

666
00:21:21,032 --> 00:21:22,192
Flounder.

667
00:21:22,432 --> 00:21:23,731
(Ingredients signaling spring)

668
00:21:23,732 --> 00:21:25,262
(Halibut)

669
00:21:25,662 --> 00:21:27,602
(Flounder)

670
00:21:27,902 --> 00:21:29,602
(Silver pomfret)

671
00:21:29,972 --> 00:21:31,942
(Other seafood such as webfoot octopus)

672
00:21:32,572 --> 00:21:35,542
(Pen shells and Manila clams for the umami flavor)

673
00:21:36,042 --> 00:21:41,011
(There are also all kinds of meat to satisfy their taste buds.)

674
00:21:41,012 --> 00:21:42,381
By the way, Chef Ho Young...

675
00:21:42,382 --> 00:21:44,262
can handle everything like the webfoot octopus.

676
00:21:44,782 --> 00:21:46,251
- Can Chef Sam Kim...
- Silver pomfret is good too.

677
00:21:46,252 --> 00:21:47,821
Handle those ingredients?

678
00:21:47,822 --> 00:21:50,138
Here's what Chef Ho Young said as soon as we got in the car.

679
00:21:50,162 --> 00:21:51,591
"Sam Kim..."

680
00:21:51,592 --> 00:21:52,691
(Trying to come between Sam and Ho Young again)

681
00:21:52,692 --> 00:21:55,031
"couldn't cook anything decent outside his cuisine."

682
00:21:55,032 --> 00:21:57,402
- If it's not his main cuisine...
- Right.

683
00:21:58,132 --> 00:22:00,401
- Do people in Italy eat them?
- They eat a lot of those.

684
00:22:00,402 --> 00:22:01,801
- I work with halibut a lot.
- Really? Halibut?

685
00:22:01,802 --> 00:22:03,231
- You work with halibut a lot?
- Halibut?

686
00:22:03,232 --> 00:22:05,042
I guess he can only work with halibut.

687
00:22:06,372 --> 00:22:08,711
Pen shells and a lot more.

688
00:22:08,712 --> 00:22:10,342
Looking at the ingredient chart,

689
00:22:10,712 --> 00:22:13,581
I can predict the dish Ho Young is going to cook.

690
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:14,681
Like what?

691
00:22:14,682 --> 00:22:16,411
- He'll steam or braise something.
- He'll steam or braise it.

692
00:22:16,412 --> 00:22:17,421
- He'll braise it.
- Right.

693
00:22:17,422 --> 00:22:19,142
- And it will be sweet.
- It will be sweet.

694
00:22:19,422 --> 00:22:21,421
- The steamed dish will be sweet?
- It will be sweet.

695
00:22:21,422 --> 00:22:23,191
The pork dish will be sweet too?

696
00:22:23,192 --> 00:22:24,498
- Everything will be sweet.
- Everything?

697
00:22:24,522 --> 00:22:25,721
He's Chef Tanghulu.

698
00:22:25,722 --> 00:22:27,038
(Suddenly going after his own teammate)

699
00:22:27,062 --> 00:22:28,261
(Chef Tanghulu)

700
00:22:28,262 --> 00:22:29,661
Watch out. He'll give you an insulin spike.

701
00:22:29,662 --> 00:22:33,731
Are there some ingredients you want us to secure?

702
00:22:33,732 --> 00:22:35,872
Silver pomfret, flounder,

703
00:22:36,132 --> 00:22:37,371
Manila clams, and webfoot octopus.

704
00:22:37,372 --> 00:22:38,701
- Flounder, Manila clams...
- Wait. I don't think...

705
00:22:38,702 --> 00:22:39,972
They're all seasonal.

706
00:22:40,172 --> 00:22:41,641
I don't think they overlap with our ingredients.

707
00:22:41,642 --> 00:22:43,411
I want halibut and Manila clams.

708
00:22:43,412 --> 00:22:44,581
- Halibut and Manila clams.
- Halibut and Manila clams.

709
00:22:44,582 --> 00:22:45,941
- I want those.
- Manila clams.

710
00:22:45,942 --> 00:22:47,112
Manila clams.

711
00:22:47,782 --> 00:22:48,981
Listen up.

712
00:22:48,982 --> 00:22:52,522
Chef Sam Kim said he wanted halibut and Manila clams.

713
00:22:52,822 --> 00:22:54,452
What if we were to take those two?

714
00:22:54,592 --> 00:22:57,262
- He won't be able to cook anything.
- He can't cook then.

715
00:22:57,522 --> 00:22:59,221
- Let's say that...
- Let's get Manila clams.

716
00:22:59,222 --> 00:23:01,461
They took halibut and Manila clams. It'd be great if they didn't.

717
00:23:01,462 --> 00:23:03,162
- Okay.
- With what can you replace them?

718
00:23:03,632 --> 00:23:04,762
I don't have a plan yet.

719
00:23:05,862 --> 00:23:07,671
(It's an emergency. He doesn't have a contingency plan.)

720
00:23:07,672 --> 00:23:08,672
Chef!

721
00:23:08,972 --> 00:23:11,012
- I told you his range was limited.
- What is this?

722
00:23:11,302 --> 00:23:12,601
- Wait.
- How...

723
00:23:12,602 --> 00:23:13,771
- He doesn't have a plan yet.
- What...

724
00:23:13,772 --> 00:23:15,211
- I need to think about it.
- What was that?

725
00:23:15,212 --> 00:23:16,811
If we keep this up,

726
00:23:16,812 --> 00:23:18,841
he might just grill some beef and pork later.

727
00:23:18,842 --> 00:23:21,081
- I can even cook Korean food.
- Of course.

728
00:23:21,082 --> 00:23:22,181
I can braise silver pomfret...

729
00:23:22,182 --> 00:23:23,211
- with the spicy sauce...
- Right.

730
00:23:23,212 --> 00:23:24,398
- and add some radishes underneath.
- Yes.

731
00:23:24,422 --> 00:23:25,621
- I can stir-fry...
- Right.

732
00:23:25,622 --> 00:23:27,321
- webfoot octopus and make it spicy.
- Exactly.

733
00:23:27,322 --> 00:23:29,022
- I can go with shabu shabu too.
- Yes.

734
00:23:29,092 --> 00:23:31,091
I can use the Manila clams for the broth...

735
00:23:31,092 --> 00:23:32,492
to make flounder stew with mugwort.

736
00:23:32,562 --> 00:23:33,562
- My gosh.
- Flounder stew with mugwort.

737
00:23:33,563 --> 00:23:35,031
- I can cook with everything.
- Flounder is in season now.

738
00:23:35,032 --> 00:23:36,568
Will his flounder stew with mugwort be sweet too?

739
00:23:36,592 --> 00:23:37,932
He might make it sweet.

740
00:23:38,032 --> 00:23:40,192
- How can that be sweet?
- That won't taste good then.

741
00:23:40,702 --> 00:23:42,732
Imagine flounder stew with mugwort being sweet.

742
00:23:42,932 --> 00:23:45,141
At this rate, my food might...

743
00:23:45,142 --> 00:23:46,802
- I...
- taste sweet even if it's not.

744
00:23:46,912 --> 00:23:48,112
- Exactly.
- All right.

745
00:23:48,372 --> 00:23:49,872
Let's begin now.

746
00:23:50,012 --> 00:23:51,481
If you play it right,

747
00:23:51,482 --> 00:23:54,081
both teams might be able to get a taste...

748
